Note:
RUNTIME API - C-RUNTIME ABI COMPATIBILITY LAYER

This file is the ABI bridge between Runa primitives and the symbol names
the legacy C runtime (runtime.c) exposed. The previous v0.0.8.4.5.3.5
runtime.o exported ~78 symbols under specific names (list_append, dict_set,
ascii_value_of, etc). Stage1 binaries link against those names.

The migration from C to Runa kept the primitive implementations under
their preferred Runa names (list_push, Dictionary.set, etc) so the
primitive layer can evolve without ABI churn. This file is the stable
re-export layer that maps:

    legacy_c_name  ->  primitive_module.canonical_name

Symbols whose names already match the primitive (e.g. allocate, memory_copy,
string_compare) do NOT appear here; they are exported directly by their
primitive files and require no wrapper.

Symbols that ONLY differ in naming convention appear as thin one-line
wrappers. The wrappers compile to a single jump and have zero runtime
overhead beyond a call/ret pair.

Symbols that have no direct primitive equivalent (integer_to_float,
float_to_integer, string_to_float, ascii_value_of, is_alpha, is_digit,
is_whitespace, memory_pointer_to_string, memory_get_substring,
memory_get_pointer_at_index, memory_set_pointer_at_index,
memory_realloc, memory_reallocate, memory_allocate, reallocate,
call_function_pointer_2args) are implemented here using inline assembly
or by composing existing primitives. This keeps the integration layer
self-contained and avoids polluting the primitive files with names that
exist solely for ABI compatibility.

Layout:

  Section 1  - Collection name aliases (lists, dicts, sets)
  Section 2  - String name aliases and missing primitives
  Section 3  - Memory aliases and indexed-pointer helpers
  Section 4  - Character classification helpers
  Section 5  - Float / integer conversion primitives
  Section 6  - Function-pointer invocation bridge
  Section 7  - Heap allocator aliases (reallocate family)
:End Note

Note: Wave MANGLING-SYMMETRIC: this file is the stable C-runtime ABI bridge.
Note: Stage1 binaries and codegen-emitted helper stubs (print_string,
Note: print_integer, exit_with_code, allocate, deallocate, memory_*, list_*,
Note: dict_*, etc.) link against the plain symbol names this file defines.
Note: Without the no-mangle sentinel the wrapper definitions emit
Note: `.globl integration_runtime_api__list_append`, breaking every legacy
Note: caller that emits `call list_append@PLT`. The per-Function flag
Note: propagation (program_tag_no_mangle_flags in main.runa /
Note: import_system.runa) tags every Function defined in this file with
Note: no_mangle=1 -- so the codegen emits plain `.globl list_append` here,
Note: AND any external caller importing this file emits a plain
Note: `call list_append@PLT` (mangling logic in codegen_resolve_call_symbol
Note: keys off the TARGET's flag, not the caller's). Calls FROM this file
Note: into the primitive layer (e.g. List.list_push) still resolve correctly
Note: because each target Function's own no_mangle flag is 0 (the primitive
Note: modules don't carry this sentinel), so the codegen emits
Note: `call collections_list__list_push@PLT` as the mangling-enabled
Note: definition demands.
Let __runa_no_mangle__ be 1

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa" as SetMod
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Heap
Import "runtime/integration/system_interface/syscall_manager.runa" as Syscall
Import "runtime/integration/system_interface/wrappers/environment_manager.runa" as EnvironmentManager

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 1 - COLLECTION NAME ALIASES
============================================================================
The C runtime used flat prefixed names (list_append, dict_set, set_union).
The Runa primitives use module-scoped names (List.push, Dictionary.set,
SetMod.union). Each alias here is a single delegating call.
:End Note

Process called "list_append" takes list_ptr as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return List.list_push(list_ptr, value)
End Process

Process called "list_find" takes list_ptr as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return List.list_index_of(list_ptr, value)
End Process

Process called "dict_create" returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.create()
End Process

Process called "dict_destroy" takes dict_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.destroy(dict_ptr)
End Process

Process called "dict_set" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.set(dict_ptr, key, value)
End Process

Process called "dict_get" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.get(dict_ptr, key)
End Process

Process called "dict_has" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.contains(dict_ptr, key)
End Process

Process called "dict_has_key" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.contains(dict_ptr, key)
End Process

Process called "dict_remove" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.remove(dict_ptr, key)
End Process

Process called "dict_size" takes dict_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.size(dict_ptr)
End Process

Process called "dict_keys" takes dict_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.keys(dict_ptr)
End Process

Process called "dict_values" takes dict_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Dictionary.values(dict_ptr)
End Process

Note:
dict_with is the value-returning entry-insert used by the canonical dictionary
literal desugar ("a dictionary containing K1 as V1, ..." in the parser). It sets
one key/value pair and returns the SAME dictionary pointer so the parser can
left-nest one call per entry as a single expression:
dict_with(dict_with(dict_create(), k1, v1), k2, v2). Dictionary.set returns a
success flag (not the dictionary), which is why a dedicated returning wrapper is
required for the expression-position desugar.
:End Note
Process called "dict_with" takes dict_ptr as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let set_status be Dictionary.set(dict_ptr, key, value)
    Return dict_ptr
End Process

Process called "set_union" takes set1_ptr as Integer, set2_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return SetMod.union(set1_ptr, set2_ptr)
End Process

Process called "set_intersection" takes set1_ptr as Integer, set2_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return SetMod.intersection(set1_ptr, set2_ptr)
End Process

Process called "set_to_list" takes set_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return SetMod.to_list(set_ptr)
End Process

Note:
set_create / set_with are the constructor and value-returning element-insert used
by the canonical set literal desugar ("a set containing E1, E2, ..." in the
parser). set_create allocates an empty set; set_with(s, e) adds one element and
returns the SAME set pointer so the parser can left-nest one call per element as
a single expression: set_with(set_with(set_create(), e1), e2). SetMod.add returns
a success flag (not the set), which is why a dedicated returning wrapper is
required for the expression-position desugar.
:End Note
Process called "set_create" returns Integer:
    Return SetMod.create()
End Process

Process called "set_with" takes set_ptr as Integer, element as Integer returns Integer:
    Let add_status be SetMod.add(set_ptr, element)
    Return set_ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 2 - STRING NAME ALIASES AND MISSING PRIMITIVES
============================================================================
string_find: aliased to string_index_of.
ascii_value_of: legacy name for "the byte at this index, or 0 on
out-of-bounds" - implemented directly here since no primitive matches.
:End Note

Process called "string_find" takes haystack as Integer, needle as Integer returns Integer:
    Return StringPrim.string_index_of(haystack, needle)
End Process

Process called "ascii_value_of" takes str as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let str_len be StringCore.string_length(str)
    If index is greater than or equal to str_len:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return Memory.memory_get_byte(str, index)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 3 - MEMORY ALIASES AND INDEXED-POINTER HELPERS
============================================================================
The C runtime had an array-style API (memory_*_pointer_at_index) which
operates on a base pointer interpreted as an array of pointers. The
Runa primitives only expose byte-offset variants. These wrappers
multiply the index by 8 (sizeof pointer on x86-64) and delegate.

memory_pointer_to_string: in C this was a pointer cast. In Runa it is
also a no-op cast because strings and pointers share the same Integer
representation.

memory_get_substring: allocates a new buffer of length+1 bytes, copies
the requested range, and null-terminates. Distinct from string_substring
which operates on string objects; this variant takes a raw byte pointer.
:End Note

Process called "memory_get_pointer_at_index" takes base as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let byte_offset be index multiplied by 8
    Return Memory.memory_get_pointer(base, byte_offset)
End Process

Process called "memory_set_pointer_at_index" takes base as Integer, index as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let byte_offset be index multiplied by 8
    Return Memory.memory_set_pointer(base, byte_offset, value)
End Process

Process called "memory_pointer_to_string" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "memory_get_substring" takes str as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let buf_size be length plus 1
    Let buf be Heap.allocate(buf_size)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_result be Memory.memory_copy(buf, str plus start, length)
    Let zero_result be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, length, 0)
    Return buf
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 3.5 - LEGACY DUNDER MEMORY INTRINSICS
============================================================================
A subset of the bootstrap-era codebase, including tests and a handful of
target-specific dispatchers (freebsd_arm64.runa, mips64.runa,
compile_orchestrator.runa) issues bare calls of the form
`__load_byte(ptr, offset)` and `__store_byte(ptr, offset, value)`.
These were intended as compiler intrinsics that lower in-line to a
single load / store instruction. The current stage1 codegen does NOT
lower them; it emits `call __load_byte@PLT` and `call __store_byte@PLT`.

Rather than carry a partial intrinsic lowering path in the codegen — which
would only solve the problem for one architecture and one calling
convention — we expose them as proper externally linkable symbols here.
Each wrapper is a single delegating tail call (one push, one call, one ret
after inlining). The semantic contract is identical to the existing
memory_get_byte / memory_set_byte primitives in core/memory_core.runa:

  __load_byte(ptr, offset)        -> unsigned byte at ptr+offset (0..255)
  __store_byte(ptr, offset, value) -> writes low 8 bits of value at ptr+offset
                                       returns 0 on success

These wrappers are part of the stable ABI alias surface and are used by
test_ieee754_binary32, test_biginteger, test_query_builder, and any other
code that predates the rename of these dunder intrinsics to their
`memory_get_byte` / `memory_set_byte` names.
:End Note

Process called "__load_byte" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_get_byte(ptr, offset)
End Process

Process called "__store_byte" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Memory.memory_set_byte(ptr, offset, value)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 4 - CHARACTER CLASSIFICATION HELPERS
============================================================================
ASCII-only classification used by lexers. Returns 1 if the input byte
satisfies the predicate, 0 otherwise. Non-ASCII bytes (>= 128) are
rejected by is_alpha and is_digit; is_whitespace accepts only the four
canonical ASCII whitespace bytes (space, tab, newline, carriage return).
:End Note

Process called "is_alpha" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_whitespace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 5 - FLOAT / INTEGER CONVERSION PRIMITIVES
============================================================================
These functions cross the integer/float boundary using SSE2 conversion
instructions:
  - cvtsi2sd  signed int64 -> binary64
  - cvttsd2si binary64 -> signed int64 (truncated toward zero)

The Runa convention is to represent IEEE-754 binary64 as an Integer
bit-pattern. So each function takes/returns Integer values whose bits
are reinterpreted at the SSE2 boundary.

string_to_float parses a decimal string into an IEEE-754 binary64 bit
pattern. The implementation handles:
  - optional leading sign
  - integer part (decimal digits)
  - optional fractional part after '.'
  - optional exponent suffix 'e' or 'E' followed by signed integer
  - leading/trailing whitespace is NOT stripped (caller's responsibility)

The algorithm uses Clinger's fast path (Clinger 1990, "How to Read
Floating Point Numbers Accurately"). For inputs whose integer mantissa
fits in 53 bits AND whose net decimal exponent is in [-22, 22], the
result is computed with a SINGLE IEEE 754 multiplication or division
against the exact power-of-10 (powers 10^0 through 10^22 are exactly
representable in binary64). Per IEEE 754, a single multiplication or
division between exactly-representable operands is correctly rounded
to nearest-even - so the result is the unique closest binary64 value
to the true mathematical product. This covers ~99% of real inputs and
fixes BF #362 (string_to_float("0.3") returning 0x3fd3333333333334
instead of the correctly-rounded 0x3fd3333333333333).

For inputs outside Clinger's range (very large |exponent| or mantissa
that does not fit in 53 bits), the implementation falls back to a
multi-step scaling path: repeated multiplication or division by the
largest exact power of ten (10^22), then a final step by the residual
power. The fallback accumulates at most ceil(|exp|/22) IEEE rounding
errors - bounded by ~7 ULPs even for the most extreme inputs near
float64's overflow/underflow boundaries. This is documented and
sufficient for compiler-internal use; user-facing numeric parsers
that require full IEEE correctly-rounded behavior across the entire
representable range should use a dedicated parser library (see
docs/dev/MEMORY_ARCHITECTURE.md for the v0.0.9.x bignum/Eisel-Lemire
roadmap).
:End Note

Note:
POW10_BITS_<n> constants are the IEEE-754 binary64 bit patterns for
10^n where n in [0, 22]. Verified exact: each value is an integer with
fewer than 53 bits of mantissa AND a binary exponent that puts the
unit-of-last-place at or above 1.0, so the float64 representation is
exact. Above 10^22, the values require more than 53 mantissa bits and
become inexact. Confirmed against Python struct.pack('<d', 10**n) for
all 23 entries.
:End Note
Constant POW10_BITS_0  as Integer is 4607182418800017408   Note: 0x3FF0000000000000 = 1.0
Constant POW10_BITS_1  as Integer is 4621819117588971520   Note: 0x4024000000000000 = 10.0
Constant POW10_BITS_2  as Integer is 4636737291354636288   Note: 0x4059000000000000 = 100.0
Constant POW10_BITS_3  as Integer is 4652007308841189376   Note: 0x408F400000000000 = 1000.0
Constant POW10_BITS_4  as Integer is 4666723172467343360   Note: 0x40C3880000000000 = 1e4
Constant POW10_BITS_5  as Integer is 4681608360884174848   Note: 0x40F86A0000000000 = 1e5
Constant POW10_BITS_6  as Integer is 4696837146684686336   Note: 0x412E848000000000 = 1e6
Constant POW10_BITS_7  as Integer is 4711630319722168320   Note: 0x416312D000000000 = 1e7
Constant POW10_BITS_8  as Integer is 4726483295884279808   Note: 0x4197D78400000000 = 1e8
Constant POW10_BITS_9  as Integer is 4741671816366391296   Note: 0x41CDCD6500000000 = 1e9
Constant POW10_BITS_10 as Integer is 4756540486875873280   Note: 0x4202A05F20000000 = 1e10
Constant POW10_BITS_11 as Integer is 4771362005757984768   Note: 0x42374876E8000000 = 1e11
Constant POW10_BITS_12 as Integer is 4786511204640096256   Note: 0x426D1A94A2000000 = 1e12
Constant POW10_BITS_13 as Integer is 4801453603149578240   Note: 0x42A2309CE5400000 = 1e13
Constant POW10_BITS_14 as Integer is 4816244402031689728   Note: 0x42D6BCC41E900000 = 1e14
Constant POW10_BITS_15 as Integer is 4831355200913801216   Note: 0x430C6BF526340000 = 1e15
Constant POW10_BITS_16 as Integer is 4846369599423283200   Note: 0x4341C37937E08000 = 1e16
Constant POW10_BITS_17 as Integer is 4861130398305394688   Note: 0x4376345785D8A000 = 1e17
Constant POW10_BITS_18 as Integer is 4876203697187506176   Note: 0x43ABC16D674EC800 = 1e18
Constant POW10_BITS_19 as Integer is 4891288408196988160   Note: 0x43E158E460913D00 = 1e19
Constant POW10_BITS_20 as Integer is 4906019910204099648   Note: 0x4415AF1D78B58C40 = 1e20
Constant POW10_BITS_21 as Integer is 4921056587992461136   Note: 0x444B1AE4D6E2EF50 = 1e21
Constant POW10_BITS_22 as Integer is 4936209963552724370   Note: 0x4480F0CF064DD592 = 1e22

Note:
CLINGER_MANTISSA_LIMIT is 2^53 = 9007199254740992. A non-negative
integer N with N < 2^53 has an exact binary64 representation (all bits
of N fit in the 52-bit explicit mantissa plus the implicit leading 1).
When BOTH operands of a multiplication or division are exact, IEEE 754
guarantees the result is correctly rounded to nearest-even.
:End Note
Constant CLINGER_MANTISSA_LIMIT as Integer is 9007199254740992

Process called "integer_to_float" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result_bits be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # n is at [rbp-8], result_bits is at [rbp-16].
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        cvtsi2sd xmm0, rax
        movq qword ptr [rbp-16], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result_bits
End Process

Note:
int_to_string is the symbol stage1 codegen auto-emits when an Integer is stringified
in a `joined with` expression. It must be provided by the runtime ABI layer so any
translation module (or other source) that uses integer interpolation links without
each file having to define its own copy. Self-contained decimal rendering via the
already-imported StringCore (char_to_string) and StringPrim (string_concat).
:End Note
Process called "int_to_string" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return "0"
    End If
    Let negative be 0
    Let n be value
    If n is less than 0:
        Set negative to 1
        Set n to 0 minus n
    End If
    Let digits be ""
    While n is greater than 0:
        Let digit be n modulo by 10
        Let code be digit plus 48
        Let ch be proc char_to_string from StringCore with code
        Set digits to proc string_concat from StringPrim with ch, digits
        Set n to n divided by 10
    End While
    If negative is equal to 1:
        Return proc string_concat from StringPrim with "-", digits
    End If
    Return digits
End Process

Process called "float_to_integer" takes float_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # float_bits is at [rbp-8], result is at [rbp-16].
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        cvttsd2si rax, xmm0
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
float_multiply_bits is an internal helper used by string_to_float to
scale the parsed mantissa by powers of ten. It takes two IEEE-754
binary64 values as Integer bit-patterns and returns their product as
an Integer bit-pattern. Implemented via SSE2 mulsd.
:End Note

Process called "float_multiply_bits" takes a_bits as Integer, b_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result_bits be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # a_bits at [rbp-8], b_bits at [rbp-16], result_bits at [rbp-24].
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        movq xmm1, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        mulsd xmm0, xmm1
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result_bits
End Process

Note:
float_divide_bits is the division counterpart to float_multiply_bits.
It computes a / b in IEEE-754 binary64, where both operands and the
result are passed as Integer bit-patterns. Implemented via SSE2
divsd. Used by string_to_float's Clinger fast path for negative
exponents: dividing by 10^k (exactly representable for k in [0, 22])
is correctly rounded and avoids the 1-ULP error that arises when
multiplying by the inexact reciprocal 0.1 ~= 0x3FB999999999999A.
:End Note

Process called "float_divide_bits" takes a_bits as Integer, b_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result_bits be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # a_bits at [rbp-8], b_bits at [rbp-16], result_bits at [rbp-24].
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        movq xmm1, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        divsd xmm0, xmm1
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result_bits
End Process

Note:
pow10_bits_lookup returns the IEEE-754 binary64 bit pattern for 10^n
where n is in [0, 22]. Returns 0 for out-of-range n (caller must
guard). Implemented as a 23-arm dispatcher rather than a table read
because the v0.0.8.5 frontend does not yet support constant arrays
in expression position; the dispatcher compiles to a simple
jump-table-equivalent sequence of compare-and-branch with no heap or
arena traffic. Branch-predictor friendly: for typical inputs the
exponent magnitude is small (literals like 3.14 use n=2) and the
early arms dominate.
:End Note

Process called "pow10_bits_lookup" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return POW10_BITS_0
    End If
    If n is equal to 1:
        Return POW10_BITS_1
    End If
    If n is equal to 2:
        Return POW10_BITS_2
    End If
    If n is equal to 3:
        Return POW10_BITS_3
    End If
    If n is equal to 4:
        Return POW10_BITS_4
    End If
    If n is equal to 5:
        Return POW10_BITS_5
    End If
    If n is equal to 6:
        Return POW10_BITS_6
    End If
    If n is equal to 7:
        Return POW10_BITS_7
    End If
    If n is equal to 8:
        Return POW10_BITS_8
    End If
    If n is equal to 9:
        Return POW10_BITS_9
    End If
    If n is equal to 10:
        Return POW10_BITS_10
    End If
    If n is equal to 11:
        Return POW10_BITS_11
    End If
    If n is equal to 12:
        Return POW10_BITS_12
    End If
    If n is equal to 13:
        Return POW10_BITS_13
    End If
    If n is equal to 14:
        Return POW10_BITS_14
    End If
    If n is equal to 15:
        Return POW10_BITS_15
    End If
    If n is equal to 16:
        Return POW10_BITS_16
    End If
    If n is equal to 17:
        Return POW10_BITS_17
    End If
    If n is equal to 18:
        Return POW10_BITS_18
    End If
    If n is equal to 19:
        Return POW10_BITS_19
    End If
    If n is equal to 20:
        Return POW10_BITS_20
    End If
    If n is equal to 21:
        Return POW10_BITS_21
    End If
    If n is equal to 22:
        Return POW10_BITS_22
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "string_to_float" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let str_len be StringCore.string_length(s)
    If str_len is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pos be 0
    Let sign be 1
    Let first_byte be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, 0)

    If first_byte is equal to 45:
        Set sign to -1
        Set pos to 1
    End If
    If first_byte is equal to 43:
        Set pos to 1
    End If

    Note: Accumulate integer part into an integer mantissa to preserve
    Note: precision; convert to float at the end via integer_to_float.
    Note: Bug #420 - int64 overflow protection: cap mantissa at 10^18 so
    Note: subsequent `* 10 + digit` cannot exceed int64 max. Float64 has
    Note: only 53 bits of mantissa (~17 sig digits) so digits beyond
    Note: that point cannot influence the rounded result anyway.
    Note: Pre-dot digits dropped bump the exponent (dropped_int_digits);
    Note: post-dot digits are simply discarded (do not bump fraction_digits).
    Let integer_mantissa be 0
    Let fraction_digits be 0
    Let saw_dot be 0
    Let dropped_int_digits be 0
    Let MANTISSA_CAP be 1000000000000000000

    While pos is less than str_len:
        Let ch be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, pos)
        If ch is equal to 46:
            If saw_dot is not equal to 0:
                Note: second dot - bail out and use what we have
                Set pos to str_len
            Otherwise:
                Set saw_dot to 1
                Set pos to pos plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 101:
                Set pos to str_len
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 69:
                    Set pos to str_len
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
                        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
                            Let digit be ch minus 48
                            If integer_mantissa is less than MANTISSA_CAP:
                                Set integer_mantissa to integer_mantissa multiplied by 10
                                Set integer_mantissa to integer_mantissa plus digit
                                If saw_dot is equal to 1:
                                    Set fraction_digits to fraction_digits plus 1
                                End If
                            Otherwise:
                                If saw_dot is equal to 0:
                                    Set dropped_int_digits to dropped_int_digits plus 1
                                End If
                            End If
                            Set pos to pos plus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Note: non-digit, non-dot, non-exponent - stop
                            Set pos to str_len
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        Set pos to str_len
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse optional exponent. pos may have stopped at 'e' or 'E';
    Note: rescan from the original buffer to find it.
    Let exp_pos be 0
    Let exp_value be 0
    Let exp_sign be 1
    Let exp_scan be 0
    While exp_scan is less than str_len:
        Let exp_ch be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, exp_scan)
        If exp_ch is equal to 101:
            Set exp_pos to exp_scan plus 1
            Set exp_scan to str_len
        Otherwise:
            If exp_ch is equal to 69:
                Set exp_pos to exp_scan plus 1
                Set exp_scan to str_len
            Otherwise:
                Set exp_scan to exp_scan plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If exp_pos is not equal to 0:
        If exp_pos is less than str_len:
            Let exp_first be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, exp_pos)
            If exp_first is equal to 45:
                Set exp_sign to -1
                Set exp_pos to exp_pos plus 1
            End If
            If exp_first is equal to 43:
                Set exp_pos to exp_pos plus 1
            End If
        End If
        While exp_pos is less than str_len:
            Let ed be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, exp_pos)
            If ed is greater than or equal to 48:
                If ed is less than or equal to 57:
                    Set exp_value to exp_value multiplied by 10
                    Set exp_value to exp_value plus (ed minus 48)
                    Set exp_pos to exp_pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set exp_pos to str_len
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set exp_pos to str_len
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Let total_exp be exp_value multiplied by exp_sign
    Set total_exp to total_exp minus fraction_digits
    Note: Bug #420 - dropped pre-dot digits contribute to positive exponent
    Set total_exp to total_exp plus dropped_int_digits

    Let mantissa_with_sign be integer_mantissa multiplied by sign
    Let result_bits be integer_to_float(mantissa_with_sign)

    Note:
    Apply 10^total_exp using Clinger's correctly-rounded fast path when
    the input fits its precondition, falling back to multi-step scaling
    otherwise. Clinger's preconditions are:
      (a) |total_exp| <= 22 (the exponent of the largest exact power of
          ten in binary64), AND
      (b) |integer_mantissa| < 2^53 (the integer mantissa is itself
          exactly representable).
    Under both preconditions a SINGLE IEEE 754 multiplication or
    division produces the correctly-rounded result by the basic IEEE
    754 guarantee for exact operands.

    Beyond Clinger's range the fallback splits the exponent into chunks
    of 22 and scales repeatedly. Each chunk uses an exact power-of-ten,
    so each individual multiply or divide is correctly rounded; the
    composition accumulates at most ceil(|total_exp|/22) <= 14 IEEE
    rounding errors over the full IEEE 754 dynamic range. Empirically
    this is within a few ULPs of the true value for all inputs within
    the binary64 representable range.
    :End Note
    If total_exp is equal to 0:
        Return result_bits
    End If

    Note:
    The Clinger eligibility check needs the magnitude of
    integer_mantissa (not the signed value). We compare against
    CLINGER_MANTISSA_LIMIT = 2^53.
    :End Note
    Let mantissa_magnitude be integer_mantissa
    If mantissa_magnitude is less than 0:
        Set mantissa_magnitude to -mantissa_magnitude
    End If

    Let exp_magnitude be total_exp
    If exp_magnitude is less than 0:
        Set exp_magnitude to -exp_magnitude
    End If

    Note:
    Clinger fast path: single exact mulsd (positive exponent) or single
    exact divsd (negative exponent). The result is correctly-rounded to
    nearest-even by IEEE 754, which is the property the slow path of
    the previous implementation lacked (repeated multiplication by 0.1,
    itself inexact, accumulated 1 ULP error per step and produced
    string_to_float("0.3") = 0x3fd3333333333334 instead of the
    correctly-rounded 0x3fd3333333333333).
    :End Note
    If exp_magnitude is less than or equal to 22:
        If mantissa_magnitude is less than CLINGER_MANTISSA_LIMIT:
            Let pow_bits be pow10_bits_lookup(exp_magnitude)
            If total_exp is greater than 0:
                Set result_bits to float_multiply_bits(result_bits, pow_bits)
            Otherwise:
                Set result_bits to float_divide_bits(result_bits, pow_bits)
            End If
            Return result_bits
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    Multi-step scaling fallback. Split exp_magnitude = k * 22 + r where
    r in [0, 21]. Apply k multiplications or divisions by 10^22, then
    a final operation by 10^r. We use the same arithmetic primitive
    (mulsd or divsd) for every step to avoid any sign confusion in the
    composed result; the choice of primitive is fixed by the sign of
    total_exp.

    Underflow/overflow behavior matches IEEE 754: multiplying past
    1.7976931348623157e308 produces +Infinity, dividing past
    5e-324 produces +0 (subnormal flush is correct per IEEE round-to-
    nearest-even). NaN propagates unchanged.
    :End Note
    Let pow22_bits be POW10_BITS_22
    Let chunks be exp_magnitude divided by 22
    Let residual be exp_magnitude minus (chunks multiplied by 22)

    Let i be 0
    If total_exp is greater than 0:
        While i is less than chunks:
            Set result_bits to float_multiply_bits(result_bits, pow22_bits)
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        If residual is greater than 0:
            Let residual_bits_pos be pow10_bits_lookup(residual)
            Set result_bits to float_multiply_bits(result_bits, residual_bits_pos)
        End If
    Otherwise:
        While i is less than chunks:
            Set result_bits to float_divide_bits(result_bits, pow22_bits)
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        If residual is greater than 0:
            Let residual_bits_neg be pow10_bits_lookup(residual)
            Set result_bits to float_divide_bits(result_bits, residual_bits_neg)
        End If
    End If

    Return result_bits
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 6 - FUNCTION-POINTER INVOCATION BRIDGE
============================================================================
call_function_pointer_2args invokes a C-ABI function pointer that takes
two integer arguments and returns an integer. Used by hashtable.runa for
caller-supplied hash / equality callbacks.

The implementation uses inline assembly to set up the System V AMD64
calling convention (rdi=arg1, rsi=arg2) and CALL through the function
pointer. The compiler-generated prologue/epilogue handles stack
alignment; the inline block only does the call.
:End Note

Process called "call_function_pointer_2args" takes fn as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # fn at [rbp-8], arg1 at [rbp-16], arg2 at [rbp-24],
        # result at [rbp-32]. Load System V argument registers
        # directly from the locals, then indirect-call the function
        # pointer in r11 (a scratch register that the callee may
        # clobber freely).
        mov rdi, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, qword ptr [rbp-24]
        mov r11, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        call r11
        mov qword ptr [rbp-32], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 7 - HEAP ALLOCATOR ALIASES (REALLOCATE FAMILY)
============================================================================
The C runtime exposed several spellings of the same operation:
  - allocate(size)                       canonical
  - deallocate(ptr)                      canonical
  - reallocate(ptr, old_size, new_size)  grows-with-zeroing variant
  - memory_realloc(ptr, new_size)        thin libc realloc
  - memory_reallocate(ptr, new_size)     alias of memory_realloc
  - memory_allocate(size)                alias of allocate

The Runa primitive layer (compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa)
already exports allocate and deallocate under those exact names. The
remaining names are re-exported from here.

reallocate is the only one that does extra work: when growing a buffer
it zero-fills the newly added bytes. This matches the legacy C
behavior and is required by callers (containers.o uses it to grow
arrays of pointers, which must read as nullptr in newly-allocated
slots).
:End Note

Process called "memory_allocate" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Heap.allocate(size)
End Process

Note:
Command-line argument ABI bridge. The C runtime (runtime.o) historically
exported these four symbols under plain names; codegen's main-prologue emits
`call runtime_set_command_line_args@PLT` (plain) when main declares
(argc, argv) -- see codegen.runa. As the pure-Runa runtime replaces
runtime.o, these plain-symbol entry points must be provided here, the
no-mangle ABI bridge, so the same call sites resolve to the Runa
implementation. Every function delegates to environment_manager, which owns
the single (global_argc, global_argv) storage; routing BOTH the set (from the
main prologue) and the get (from user code) through that one owner guarantees
they observe the same argv -- eliminating the dual-storage split that occurs
when runtime.o and environment_manager each define their own global_argv.
:End Note

Process called "runtime_set_command_line_args" takes argc as Integer, argv as Integer returns Integer:
    Return EnvironmentManager.runtime_set_command_line_args(argc, argv)
End Process

Process called "set_command_line_args" takes argc as Integer, argv as Integer returns Integer:
    Return EnvironmentManager.set_command_line_args(argc, argv)
End Process

Process called "get_command_line_arg" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return EnvironmentManager.get_command_line_arg(index)
End Process

Process called "get_command_line_arg_count" returns Integer:
    Return EnvironmentManager.get_command_line_arg_count()
End Process

Process called "memory_realloc" takes ptr as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    libc-realloc-compatible reallocate. Grows or shrinks the allocation
    at ptr to new_size bytes, preserving the prefix bytes that fit in
    both old and new buffers. Returns a new pointer (which may equal
    ptr in a future in-place-grow optimization; current implementation
    always allocates fresh and copies).

    THE OLD SOURCE COPY SIZE IS BOUNDED BY THE OLD USER-BUFFER SIZE.
    The naive implementation that copies new_size source bytes is
    INCORRECT when growing: the old buffer is by definition smaller
    than new_size, so the source-side read walks past the end of the
    old allocation. On heap layouts where the old block ends at a
    page boundary the read faults with SIGSEGV; on the ASan-class
    canary layout the read triggers QUARANTINE_EVICT (loc=5) on the
    next eviction because the OOB read disturbs an adjacent
    quarantined block's canary.

    Correct behavior: query the actual user-buffer size via
    Heap.allocator_user_size and clamp the copy to min(old, new).
    For grow operations the trailing (new_size - old_size) bytes of
    the new buffer are NOT zero-initialized by this function; if
    callers require zeroing they must use reallocate(ptr, old_size,
    new_size) which has that contract.
    :End Note
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return Heap.allocate(new_size)
    End If
    If new_size is equal to 0:
        Let _free be Heap.deallocate(ptr)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_ptr be Heap.allocate(new_size)
    If new_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Query the actual size of the user buffer at ptr. allocator_user_size
    Note: dispatches identically to deallocate's E3 fast path: pool slots
    Note: return their slab's slot_size, brk/mmap allocations return
    Note: total_size minus header_size minus optional post-canary.
    Let old_size be Heap.allocator_user_size(ptr)

    Note: Clamp the copy length to min(old_size, new_size) so we never
    Note: read past the end of the old user buffer. This is the fix for
    Note: the OOB-read SIGSEGV/canary cluster observed in P2-F Wave 1.
    Let copy_len be new_size
    If old_size is less than copy_len:
        Set copy_len to old_size
    End If
    Let _copy be Memory.memory_copy(new_ptr, ptr, copy_len)
    Let _free be Heap.deallocate(ptr)
    Return new_ptr
End Process

Process called "memory_reallocate" takes ptr as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    Return memory_realloc(ptr, new_size)
End Process

Process called "reallocate" takes ptr as Integer, old_size as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Let fresh be Heap.allocate(new_size)
        If fresh is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: allocate guarantees zero-filled memory, so no extra
        Note: zeroing is needed for the entire fresh buffer.
        Return fresh
    End If
    If new_size is equal to 0:
        Let _free be Heap.deallocate(ptr)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_ptr be Heap.allocate(new_size)
    If new_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let bytes_to_copy be old_size
    If new_size is less than old_size:
        Set bytes_to_copy to new_size
    End If
    Let _copy be Memory.memory_copy(new_ptr, ptr, bytes_to_copy)
    If new_size is greater than old_size:
        Let zero_start be new_ptr plus old_size
        Let zero_len be new_size minus old_size
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than zero_len:
            Let _zb be Memory.memory_set_byte(zero_start, i, 0)
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Let _release be Heap.deallocate(ptr)
    Return new_ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SECTION 8 - PROCESS-EXIT BRIDGE (codegen-emitted error handler symbol)
============================================================================
The codegen emits `.null_pointer_error`, `.bounds_error_negative`, and
`.bounds_error_overflow` runtime-panic stubs in every translation unit. Each
stub ends with `call exit_with_code@PLT`. With mangling enabled, the
canonical syscall_manager.runa exports
`system_interface_syscall_manager__exit_with_code` -- no plain `exit_with_code`
symbol exists in the build_runtime tree. This file is `__runa_no_mangle__`,
so its `exit_with_code` Process definition emits a plain `.globl
exit_with_code` that satisfies the codegen's PLT reference. The body
delegates to the canonical syscall_manager implementation via the qualified
call, which under per-Function mangling resolves to the mangled symbol
(target's no_mangle=0). Zero-cost adapter: one tail-style call.
:End Note

Process called "exit_with_code" takes code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return Syscall.exit_with_code(code)
End Process
